<div id="p697" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#6&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=697#p697">2009-10-19 03:37:06</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=90590">fuzzel</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: BEP 31 Tracker Failure Retry Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>The &quot;Accident&quot; can easily be found on Google:<br /><a href="http://www.google.com/search?q=The+Pirate+Bay+sixxs.org" rel="nofollow">http://www.google.com/search?q=The+Pirate+Bay+sixxs.org</a><br /><br />In short: IPv6Gate is a IPv6&lt;-&gt;IPv4 gateway. TPB was down a couple of times but available over IPv6, thus reachable through that, and as the tracker protocol is running on top of a minimal HTTP, people started inserting the tracker hostname but with .sixxs.org behind it, even though that was blocked since the beginning (to avoid load issues, and also to be able to tell Paramount and other stupid illegal-download hunters that the hosts are not trackers). I guess people thought it worked, as something like <a href="http://www.thepiratebay.org.sixxs.org" rel="nofollow">www.thepiratebay.org.sixxs.org</a> does work, which is correct as that is just a normal website.<br /><br />Thus, now we are receiving about about half a million hits/sec for queries like /announce/ and /scrape. We tried 404s which is what we did originally, and now 301's, redirecting them to the TPB tracker as that is what The_8472 suggest might work, but it seems those clients keep on hammering on the boxes. Heck, we had to add a box so that the normal IPv6Gate function could keep on working.<br /><br />The user can't do much about it, and there is no way for them to 'stop' requests, they also don't care about it, as long as they get their stuff.<br /><br />The server (eg us) can't tell the client to stop either.<br /><br />As such, this request, so that clients that get something like this implemented so that it can request those clients to just buzzz off.<br /><br />Easiest would be if Torrent clients just behaved properly according to HTTP standards and handled 'HTTP 404' (Not Found) or 'HTTP 403' (Forbidden) correctly. But it seems at least the Azureus devs seem to have had issues with 404s which where being returned from broken PHP-based trackers (I wonder how it can return a 404 though) and seem to favor hammering on websites which actually don't have a tracker instead of telling the user &quot;hey this doesn't work at the moment, maybe try again later&quot;....<br /><br />As such, as apparently Torrent clients are made for hammering sites and getting what they need, this proposal for an extension, so that there is at least one way to tell clients to buzz off and never come back.<br /><br />(Yes, the installed base will keep on hammering, but hopefully people do upgrade their clients once in a while, thus it will slowly go away... just call it a security upgrade, which effectively it is as we could for instance now 301 those clients to an unsuspecting site and they would nicely get 500k hits/sec extra, can they cope with that? Directing it at a &quot;heavy&quot; page like something doing a lot of DB queries should have the proper effect.... good that we have no evil intentions eh <img src="img/smilies/wink.png" width="15" height="15" alt="wink" /></p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

