<div id="p708" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#12&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=708#p708">2009-10-23 16:30:44</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=90590">fuzzel</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: BEP 31 Tracker Failure Retry Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>&gt; why would you want to match ALL bittorrent trackers?<br /><br />Because of the high amount of queries, which we don't want, especially as it is BitTorrent Tracker requests, and not HTTP/Website traffic for which the system is meant.<br /><br />If it was true HTTP, it would not be there because the clients would understand a 404 and other things we tried for telling them to buzz off.<br /><br />&gt; I thought that this was about traffic, obviously you'd only have to match those that<br />&gt; cause a disproportional amount of traffic, which should be a quite small amount, no?<br /><br />Why try to figure out the bad ones if just blocking /announce + /scrape solves the problem? For that matter, we could also match on User Agent, but then again, we can't signal to the client that the data they are requesting is not there as the BitTorrent clients don't properly handle HTTP error codes and just keep on coming back; ergo..... the whole idea as written up in this proposal <img src="img/smilies/wink.png" width="15" height="15" alt="wink" /><br /><br />&gt; Not to mention that you're more or less providing an open proxy...<br /><br />For websites (real HTTP) more or less true not for BitTorrent trackers (some kind of misformed HTTP due to the clients not supporting it).<br /><br />&gt; I'm not really convinced that this is actually a common scenario.<br /><br />Why is it so difficult to accept that some people DON'T want to get requests from certain clients and would want the ability to tell those clients that they should stop hammering on them?<br /><br />&gt; Not to mention that - as i have stated earlier - that redirecting to the correct URL<br />&gt; would be a much cleaner choice as your website is clearly meant to act as a proxy,<br /><br />For this case, this is a possibility. But it does not work, as we have demonstrated by trying to send 301s and redirecting the clients to the real tracker. The clients, as you have stated yourself ignore these more or less as they try it the first time and then still come back, at the same rate as before; as such this does not solve the problem in any way.<br /><br />&gt; redirecting to an un-proxied URL wouldn't deprive torrents of their trackers, simply<br />&gt; telling them to never come back again on the other hand would.<br /><br />So, someone hardcodes for example <a href="http://www.bittorent.org" rel="nofollow">www.bittorent.org</a> in a popular torrent, because of that the site, even though it does not actually have a bittorrent tracker will get a zillion of requests!?<br /><br />Or even in another situation: somebody sets up a tracker (one of those PHP ones) on a shared hosting environment, this takes that host effectively down as it becomes popular, thus the ISP wants that site off that shared environment, but it does not have control over DNS, should the ISP then just null route that IP or something?<br /><br />I can see a lot of cases where there will be even a real tracker which will want to tell the clients to just buzz off for a short time or permanently.<br /><br />Which is why this proposal is there...</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
